
  <sn><md>#### **Q. List functions of earthworm population in improving soil quality.**

Earthworms offer many benefits by their activity in the soil. Functions of earthworms in improving soil quality are listed below-

![diagram](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/SES3/Soil%20and%20Enviromental%20Quality/resources/soil-quality-dgrm-17.png)

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
**a. Increase nutrient availability:** Worms `feed on plant debris` (dead roots, grasses, leaves, manure) and soil. Their `digestive system concentrates the organic and mineral constituents` in the food they eat. As a result `their casts are richer in available nutrients` than the soil around them. ++Nitrogen++ in the casts is `readily available to plants`. A large quantities of nutrients (N, P, K, and Ca) are derived from earthworm `urine and mucus`.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
![img](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/SES3/Soil%20and%20Enviromental%20Quality/resources/soil-quality-dgrm-14.png)
:::
:::


:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
![img](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/SES3/Soil%20and%20Enviromental%20Quality/resources/soil-quality-dgrm-15.png)
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
**b. Provide better drainage:** The `extensive channeling and burrowing` by earthworms `loosens and aerates the soil` and improves soil drainage. Soils with earthworms `drain up to 10 times faster` than soils without earthworms.
:::
:::


**c. Provide a more stable soil structure:** Earthworm ++casts++ work as a `cementing agent` and bind soil particles together to form `water-stable aggregates`. These ++water stable aggregates++ are able to `store moisture without dispersing`. Research has shown that earthworms which leave their casts on the soil surface `rebuild topsoil`.


:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
**d. Improve farm productivity:** In New Zealand and Tasmania research on earthworms has found that earthworms introduced to `worm-free perennial pastures` produced an initial increase of `70-80%` in pasture growth. Researchers also found that the most productive pastures in the worm trials had up to 7 million worms per hectare, weighing 2.4 tons. Besides there was a `close correlation between pasture productivity and total worm weight`.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
![img](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/SES3/Soil%20and%20Enviromental%20Quality/resources/soil-quality-dgrm-16.png)
:::
:::</md></sn>
